  "business_context": "Form Submission records are the bridge between web forms and the CRM data model. When a visitor fills out \"Request a Demo\" or \"Subscribe to Newsletter\" or \"Donate Now,\" a Form Submission record captures what they submitted (field values), where they submitted from (page URL, referrer), and what CRM record got created or updated as a result. This serves three purposes: (1) data lineage — proves which form drove which CRM record's creation, useful for marketing-attribution and data-quality audits; (2) field-mapping flexibility — form fields don't have to map one-to-one with CRM fields, so the submission record preserves the original input even if mapping is imperfect; (3) duplicate-handling — the submission can be analyzed to decide whether to create a new contact or update an existing one. HubSpot is the system that elevates Form Submission to a first-class entity most prominently — Forms are managed in HubSpot, submissions are tracked, and HubSpot Forms are a major lead-capture mechanism. Other systems treat form submissions as upstream events that produce Contact / Lead records but don't preserve the submission itself as a queryable entity. When interviewing clients, surface \"Form Submission\" by asking whether they need to track the source form for each new contact / lead and whether they need to retain the original submission data separately from the CRM record.",
